# Internshala Internships – Complete Guide 2026

This guide is written for all Indian students and recent graduates seeking internships through Internshala in 2026.

It covers:
- School students in 11th and 12th
- First- and second-year college students with little or no experience
- Third- and fourth-year undergraduates looking for paid opportunities
- Final-year students, postgraduates, and gap-year candidates targeting higher-stipend, remote, or brand-name roles

Internshala remains the largest platform in India for student internships and entry-level opportunities. As of early March 2026, the platform lists approximately 8,800–9,200 active internships, of which roughly 3,000 are work-from-home or fully remote. Over 3.2 crore students are registered, and more than 28 lakh internships or fresher roles have been facilitated to date.

The information below is based on current platform behaviour, typical company requirements, and real application patterns observed in 2025–2026.

## 1. Current Landscape on Internshala (March 2026)

Internshala continues to be the primary channel for students because most listings explicitly accept candidates with limited or no prior experience.

Key numbers observed in early 2026:
- Total active internships: 8,754–9,200 (varies daily; highest during February–May)
- Work-from-home / remote listings: 2,900–3,200
- Listings marked women-preferred: around 4,400
- Roles offering ₹10,000+ stipend: approximately 4,000–4,500
- Dominant categories:
  - Digital Marketing / Social Media / Content Marketing
  - Content Writing / Copywriting / Blogging
  - Graphic Design / Video Editing / UI/UX basics
  - Software Development / Web Development / App Development
  - Data Analytics / Data Science / Machine Learning
  - Business Development / Sales
  - Human Resources / Recruitment / Operations
  - Finance & Accounting support roles

Stipend distribution:
- Most common range: ₹5,000–₹25,000 per month
- Higher end (tech, product, marketing roles in funded startups): ₹25,000–₹50,000 (less frequent)
- Around 5–10% of interns in technical or high-performing roles receive Pre-Placement Offers leading to full-time employment.

The platform is especially useful for students in tier-2 and tier-3 cities because remote roles form a large portion of listings.

## 2. Eligibility – Who Can Apply

Internshala has very few strict barriers.

Eligible candidates include:
- Students in 11th and 12th (mainly content, design, social media, data entry)
- First- and second-year undergraduates (wide range of non-technical and entry-level roles)
- Third- and fourth-year undergraduates (B.Tech, BCA, B.Com, BA, etc.)
- Final-year students and postgraduates (MCA, MBA, M.Tech, etc.)
- Students with academic backlogs or gap years (explain gaps clearly if asked)
- Students from smaller towns and cities (Shirpur, Dhule, and similar locations benefit heavily from remote filters)

Most companies do not enforce strict CGPA cutoffs. A CGPA above 7.0 can help when applying to larger brands, but it is rarely a hard requirement.

## 3. Step-by-Step Application Process

### 3.1 Profile Completion (Highest Priority)

A fully completed profile receives significantly more views from employers.

Steps:
1. Register at https://internshala.com using email or Google account.
2. Complete every section:
   - Education details (institute name, course, branch, year of study, expected graduation)
   - Skills (list realistically – include even basic tools: MS Office, Google Workspace, Canva, Python, HTML/CSS, social media management)
   - Projects, achievements, positions of responsibility, extracurricular activities
   - Work samples (Google Drive folder with public link, GitHub repository, Behance portfolio, personal blog, Instagram page managed)
3. Use the built-in AI resume builder and download the PDF version.
4. Write the "About me" section (3–5 sentences maximum).

Example for a first-year student:
"First-year B.Com student from Maharashtra interested in digital marketing and content creation. Self-learned Canva and basic video editing tools. Managed local event promotions reaching 500+ people. Looking to gain practical experience in remote marketing or content roles."

Example for a final-year student:
"Final-year Computer Science student with hands-on experience in three full-stack projects using MERN technologies. Completed Internshala certifications in Python and Data Structures. Seeking remote software development or backend roles to contribute to live product features."

### 3.2 Searching and Filtering

Main page: https://internshala.com/internships

Recommended filters:
- Work from home (essential for students in smaller towns)
- Stipend: ₹5,000+ or ₹10,000+
- Start date: Immediately or within 1 month
- Category: match your field of interest
- Actively hiring (green indicator – faster response rate)
- Part-time (if full-time clashes with college schedule)

Save the filtered search and enable email notifications.

### 3.3 Writing Strong Applications

Most postings include 1–3 custom questions. Generic or copied answers are almost always rejected.

Frequently asked questions and effective response patterns:

1. Why should we hire you for this internship?

   Avoid: "I am hardworking and eager to learn."
   
   Better (example – social media role):
   "I have managed an Instagram page for a local event series, growing it to 1,200 followers with average engagement of 18%. I regularly create Reels and static posts using Canva and CapCut, follow current trends, and understand basic scheduling and analytics tools. I can produce 10–15 pieces of content weekly and help improve reach and interaction metrics."

2. Relevant experience or projects?

   Even with minimal experience:
   - College fest poster designs created in Canva
   - Sample campaign plan prepared during free online training
   - Volunteer role managing social media for a small organisation
   - Personal blog with 6–10 published articles

3. Why this company or role?

   Show minimal research:
   "I noticed that your company uses automated workflows to handle customer queries. Having completed a short course on AI basics, I am interested in supporting the testing and refinement of such features."

Attach the resume PDF in every application.

Target: 70–150 thoughtful applications over 4–6 weeks for most first-time applicants.

### 3.4 After Submission

- Response time: 2–10 days (some companies reply within hours)
- Check spam/junk folders for emails from internshala.com
- Prepare for telephonic or video interviews (most common format)

Common interview questions:
- Tell me about yourself (60–90 seconds: education → skills → motivation → one achievement)
- Why this field?
- Strengths with examples
- Weakness you are working on
- How do you manage tight deadlines?
- Why our company?
- Basic technical questions (for development or data roles)

After the interview, send a short thank-you message summarising your continued interest.

## 4. Strategies by Experience Level

**Students with zero or very low experience:**
- Focus on content writing, social media, graphic design, HR support, data entry, virtual assistance
- Complete 1–2 free Internshala trainings (certificates appear on profile)
- Create a small portfolio quickly (5–10 Canva designs, 2–3 blog posts, sample social media content)
- Apply only to roles tagged "no prior experience required"

**Students with some college projects or activities:**
- Target roles offering ₹8,000–₹18,000 stipend
- Include college fest roles, group projects, small freelance tasks
- Link to GitHub, Behance, or personal website
- Follow up politely after 5–7 days if no response

**Final-year and postgraduate students:**
- Target ₹15,000–₹40,000+ stipends and larger organisations
- Apply within the first 48 hours of posting
- Highlight hackathons, certifications (Google, AWS, Coursera), open-source contributions
- Be prepared to discuss multiple offers if shortlisted by several companies

## 5. Application Tracking

Use a simple spreadsheet with these columns:
- Date of application
- Company name
- Role title
- Stipend mentioned
- Application ID or link
- Custom questions answered (yes/no)
- Current status (Applied → Shortlisted → Interview Scheduled → Offer → Rejected)
- Next follow-up date
- Notes on feedback or improvements

## 6. Common Reasons Applications Are Rejected

- Incomplete profile
- Generic or copied answers to custom questions
- Applying to roles unrelated to skills or location preferences
- Missing resume attachment
- No follow-up after shortlisting
- Falling for paid "registration" or "guaranteed internship" offers (all legitimate opportunities are free)

## 7. Internshala Training Courses

Placement-guarantee programs (refund policy if no placement):
- Full Stack Web Development
- Data Science
- Digital Marketing
- UI/UX Design
- Human Resources
- Product Management

Free short courses:
- Python for Beginners
- Digital Marketing Fundamentals
- Graphic Design
- HR Basics

Certificates from these courses improve profile visibility.

## 8. Timing and Location Considerations

- February to May: highest number of summer internships
- June to August: fewer new postings; focus on roles starting later in the year
- Students in Shirpur, Dhule, or similar locations: use the "Work from home" filter consistently – most remote roles do not require physical presence

## 9. Final Notes

The first internship usually requires the most applications and patience. Rejection rates are high in the beginning but decrease as profile quality, answers, and interview skills improve.

Maintain consistency: apply regularly, track everything, refine answers based on feedback.

All information is current as of March 2026.

Good luck with your applications.
